Emotional Etymology & Affective Geometry v1.0

Core claim

Emotions are not just labels. They can be modeled as:
	•	historical meanings carried by words
	•	structured positions in an affect-space
	•	dynamic transformations between states
	•	cross-domain control signals for behavior, narrative, markets, groups, and governance

So the framework has three layers:

etymology → geometry → application

⸻

1. Formal model

Let an emotional state be represented as a vector:

E = (v, a, d, c, t, g, s)

Where:
	•	v = valence
positive / negative / mixed / neutral
	•	a = activation
low to high energy
	•	d = direction
toward / away / against / none
	•	c = certainty or legibility
how mapped or unmapped the state feels
	•	t = attachment intensity
how much the self is invested
	•	g = agency
felt ability to act
	•	s = social orientation
self / dyad / group / world

That gives you a way to compare emotions structurally instead of only by name.

Example sketches

Fear
	•	negative valence
	•	high activation
	•	away-oriented
	•	low certainty
	•	medium to high attachment
	•	low or unstable agency
	•	often self-preservational social orientation

Courage
	•	mixed valence
	•	high activation
	•	toward-oriented
	•	higher certainty
	•	high attachment
	•	high agency
	•	self or prosocial orientation

Apathy
	•	near-neutral or flattened valence
	•	low activation
	•	no direction
	•	low attachment
	•	low agency
	•	low social investment

