2. Triadic law

A lot of emotional systems are not binary oppositions. They are triads.

General form:
	•	positive engagement
	•	negative engagement
	•	zero engagement

So instead of “opposites,” use:

Canonical triads
	•	Love / Hate / Apathy
	•	Fear / Courage / Apathy
	•	Desire / Aversion / Indifference
	•	Trust / Distrust / Disinterest
	•	Hope / Despair / Resignation
	•	Curiosity / Anxiety / Boredom
	•	Pride / Shame / Emptiness
	•	Engagement / Resistance / Withdrawal

Why this matters

Love and hate are opposite in direction, but close in energy.
Apathy is opposite in engagement intensity.

That means the third point is often not “the opposite emotion,” but the null state.

⸻

3. Etymology layer

Emotional etymology asks:

What action-logic or embodied geometry is hidden in the word’s history?

Not as proof, but as clue.

Examples of the kind of thing to look for:
	•	roots implying movement
	•	pressure
	•	burden
	•	absence
	•	heart / center
	•	division
	•	expansion / contraction
	•	binding / loosening

This gives you a hypothesis about the emotional state’s original behavioral role.

Rule

Etymology is evidence of conceptual ancestry, not final ontology.

So:
	•	useful as a diagnostic scaffold
	•	not sufficient by itself
	•	must survive present usage and empirical reality

⸻

4. Geometry of emotion

Treat emotional space as a field, not a list.

Emotional states can behave like:
	•	vectors
	•	attractors
	•	repellers
	•	basins
	•	thresholds
	•	null zones
	•	oscillations

That means you can model:
	•	how states pull behavior
	•	how people get stuck
	•	where transitions become likely
	•	what interventions work

Minimal geometry

A simple map could use three axes:
	•	X: valence
	•	Y: activation
	•	Z: certainty / agency

More advanced versions can add:
	•	temporal persistence
	•	social contagion
	•	narrative framing
	•	bodily load

