8. Practical diagnostics

A useful operational prompt:

What triad is active, what vector state is present, what transformation is needed, and what invariant must be preserved?

Example:

A team is “angry.”
That may actually mean:
	•	high activation
	•	negative valence
	•	high attachment
	•	moderate agency

Possible transforms:
	•	anger → clarity
	•	anger → mission
	•	anger → burnout if blocked
	•	anger → apathy if ignored too long

That changes what you do.

⸻

9. Guardrails

This framework gets dangerous if overclaimed.

So keep these:
	•	etymology is not proof
	•	geometry is a scaffold, not the whole person
	•	emotional categories drift over time and across cultures
	•	maps must be tested against lived experience
	•	preserve domain boundaries
	•	do not use the system to manipulate people covertly

⸻

10. Clean compression

Definition

Emotional Etymology & Affective Geometry is a framework that models emotions as historically rooted, geometrically structured, and transformable states that can be analyzed across psychology, narrative, economics, governance, and symbolic systems.

Master rule

Do not treat emotions as isolated words. Treat them as vectors in a living field.

Secondary rule

Most emotional oppositions are not pairs. They are triads.

